To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A

Kanshudo Component Builder is a very fast way to look up kanji. Draw a component, type its name, or look it up in a list. Access the Component Builder wherever you see the 部 icon, e.g. in
Quick Search
at the top right of every page. For detailed instructions, see our how-to guide.

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

You can use Kanshudo to study for the JLPT. Kanshudo usefulness levels for kanji, words and grammar points map directly to JLPT levels, so your mastery level on Kanshudo is a direct indicator of your readiness for the JLPT exams.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0AKanshudo usefulness counts up from 1, whereas the JLPT counts down from 5 - so the first JLPT level, N5, is equivalent to Kanshudo usefulness level .https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80%0A

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

The JLPT (Japanese Language Proficiency Test, 日本語能力試験) is the standard test of Japanese language ability for non-Japanese.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80 would first come up in levelhttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80N.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80

Kanshudo displays a badge indicating which level of the JLPT words, kanji and grammar points might first be used in:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
indicates N5 (the first and easiest level)
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
indicates N1 (the highest and most difficult)

You can use Kanshudo to study for the JLPT. Kanshudo usefulness levels for kanji, words and grammar points map directly to JLPT levels, so your mastery level on Kanshudo is a direct indicator of your readiness for the JLPT exams.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80Kanshudo usefulness counts up from 1, whereas the JLPT counts down from 5 - so the first JLPT level, N5, is equivalent to Kanshudo usefulness level .https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%80
The JLPT vocabulary lists were compiled by Wikipedia and Tanos from past papers. Sometimes the form listed by the sources is not the most useful form. In case of doubt, we advise you to learn the Kanshudo recommended form. Words that appear in the JLPT lists in a different form are indicated with a lighter colored 'shadow' badge, like this: .

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A

Kanshudo Component Builder Drawing Help
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

The JLPT (Japanese Language Proficiency Test, 日本語能力試験) is the standard test of Japanese language ability for non-Japanese.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A would first come up in levelhttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0AN.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
Kanshudo displays a badge indicating which level of the JLPT words, kanji and grammar points might first be used in:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
indicates N5 (the first and easiest level)
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
indicates N1 (the highest and most difficult)
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
You can use Kanshudo to study for the JLPT. Kanshudo usefulness levels for kanji, words and grammar points map directly to JLPT levels, so your mastery level on Kanshudo is a direct indicator of your readiness for the JLPT exams.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0AKanshudo usefulness counts up from 1, whereas the JLPT counts down from 5 - so the first JLPT level, N5, is equivalent to Kanshudo usefulness level .https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF%0A
The JLPT vocabulary lists were compiled by Wikipedia and Tanos from past papers. Sometimes the form listed by the sources is not the most useful form. In case of doubt, we advise you to learn the Kanshudo recommended form. Words that appear in the JLPT lists in a different form are indicated with a lighter colored 'shadow' badge, like this: .

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BFhttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF

https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BFhttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BFhttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%BF

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A

Quick Search
at the top right of every page. For detailed instructions, see our how-to guide.

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. The JLPT (Japanese Language Proficiency Test, 日本語能力試験) is the standard test of Japanese language ability for non-Japanese.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A would first come up in levelhttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0AN.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A

indicates N5 (the first and easiest level)
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
indicates N1 (the highest and most difficult)

You can use Kanshudo to study for the JLPT. Kanshudo usefulness levels for kanji, words and grammar points map directly to JLPT levels, so your mastery level on Kanshudo is a direct indicator of your readiness for the JLPT exams.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0AKanshudo usefulness counts up from 1, whereas the JLPT counts down from 5 - so the first JLPT level, N5, is equivalent to Kanshudo usefulness level .https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8%0A

In case of doubt, we advise you to learn the Kanshudo recommended form. Words that appear in the JLPT lists in a different form are indicated with a lighter colored 'shadow' badge, like this: .

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%A8

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

The JLPT (Japanese Language Proficiency Test, 日本語能力試験) is the standard test of Japanese language ability for non-Japanese.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A would first come up in levelhttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0AN.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A

https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
indicates N5 (the first and easiest level)
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
indicates N1 (the highest and most difficult)

You can use Kanshudo to study for the JLPT. Kanshudo usefulness levels for kanji, words and grammar points map directly to JLPT levels, so your mastery level on Kanshudo is a direct indicator of your readiness for the JLPT exams.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0AKanshudo usefulness counts up from 1, whereas the JLPT counts down from 5 - so the first JLPT level, N5, is equivalent to Kanshudo usefulness level .https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6%0A
The JLPT vocabulary lists were compiled by Wikipedia and Tanos from past papers. Sometimes the form listed by the sources is not the most useful form. In case of doubt, we advise you to learn the Kanshudo recommended form. Words that appear in the JLPT lists in a different form are indicated with a lighter colored 'shadow' badge, like this: .

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B8%B6

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A

at the top right of every page. For detailed instructions, see our how-to guide.

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. You can use Kanshudo to study for the JLPT. Kanshudo usefulness levels for kanji, words and grammar points map directly to JLPT levels, so your mastery level on Kanshudo is a direct indicator of your readiness for the JLPT exams.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0AKanshudo usefulness counts up from 1, whereas the JLPT counts down from 5 - so the first JLPT level, N5, is equivalent to Kanshudo usefulness level .https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E%0A

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8Ehttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8Ehttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E
Not finding your component?
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E3%83%8E

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99%0A

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

The JLPT (Japanese Language Proficiency Test, 日本語能力試験) is the standard test of Japanese language ability for non-Japanese.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99 would first come up in levelhttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99N.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
Kanshudo displays a badge indicating which level of the JLPT words, kanji and grammar points might first be used in:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
indicates N5 (the first and easiest level)
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
indicates N1 (the highest and most difficult)
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99

https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
You can use Kanshudo to study for the JLPT. Kanshudo usefulness levels for kanji, words and grammar points map directly to JLPT levels, so your mastery level on Kanshudo is a direct indicator of your readiness for the JLPT exams.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99Kanshudo usefulness counts up from 1, whereas the JLPT counts down from 5 - so the first JLPT level, N5, is equivalent to Kanshudo usefulness level .https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99
The JLPT vocabulary lists were compiled by Wikipedia and Tanos from past papers. Sometimes the form listed by the sources is not the most useful form. In case of doubt, we advise you to learn the Kanshudo recommended form. Words that appear in the JLPT lists in a different form are indicated with a lighter colored 'shadow' badge, like this: .
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%99

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A

The Kanshudo Component Builder can recognize any of the 416 components listed in the chart below the drawing area. Tips:
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  • Draw a component in the center of the area, as large as you can
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  • Try to draw the component as it appears in the kanji you're looking up
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  • Don't worry about stroke order or number of strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
  • Don't draw more than one component at a time
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A

Kanshudo tracks your mastery (knowledge) of every kanji, word and grammar point in Japanese individually. In item searches (Kanji search, Word search and Grammar search), you will see a small circle with a number from 0 - 4 next to each item, where zero means 'no mastery' and 4 means 'absolute mastery'. A summary of your mastery data is displayed in your Kanji, Word and Grammar mastery wheels.

You can use Kanshudo to study for the JLPT. Kanshudo usefulness levels for kanji, words and grammar points map directly to JLPT levels, so your mastery level on Kanshudo is a direct indicator of your readiness for the JLPT exams.https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0AKanshudo usefulness counts up from 1, whereas the JLPT counts down from 5 - so the first JLPT level, N5, is equivalent to Kanshudo usefulness level .https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A%0A

The pitch accent markings show you how to pronounce a word. A line underneath a kana symbol indicates low pitch, and a line above indicates high pitch. A vertical line at the end indicates the pitch of the next sound in a sentence using the word is different to the last sound of the word. The number(s) to the right of the markings show how this pitch is represented in a Japanese dictionary.

To find any kanji, first try to identify the components it is made up of. Once you have identified any component, search for it in any of three ways:https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
  1. Draw it in the drawing area
    2. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
  2. Type the name in the text area
    3. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
  3. Look for it in the list
    4. https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9Ahttps://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
Example: look up 漢
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
    https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
  • Notice that 漢 is made of several components: 氵 艹 口 夫
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
  • Draw any of these components (one at a time) in the drawing area, and select it when you see it
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
  • Alternatively, look for a component in the list. 氵 艹 口 each have three strokes; 夫 has four strokes
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
  • If you know the meanings of the components, type any of them in the text area: water (氵), grass (艹), mouth (口) or husband (夫)
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
  • Keep adding components until you can see your kanji in the list of matches that appears near the top.
    • https://www.kanshudo.com/searchcg?q=%E4%B9%9A
